    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-09-08T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-09-08T07:00:00-05:00" n="212"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d212">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/15354: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-08T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 8, 1939—1 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 8—12:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1842. I communicated the contents of your 818, September 7, 7 p.m.<note n="10"
                        xml:id="d212fn10">See footnote 8a, <ref target="#pg_238">p.
                        238</ref>.</note> to Leger<note n="11" xml:id="d212fn11">Secretary General
                        of the French Foreign Office.</note> this morning. He replied that the
                    information reached him most opportunely since he had received this morning from
                    the British Foreign Office a statement of the views of the British Government on
                    this subject.</p>
                <p>He gave me briefly the gist of the British position which was: that unless the
                    Government of the United States prepared to take an energetic position with
                    regard to this matter the British Government would feel obliged to withdraw all
                    British troops from China giving as an excuse the need for such troops in
                    Europe.</p>
                <p>Leger expressed his profound gratitude for the information which I had been able
                    to give him.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
